{
    "level": "A1",
    "intro": "The patterns <strong>have got / has got</strong> help you say <strong>what someone has</strong>: an object, a pet, a family member, or another simple possession.",
    "rules": [
        {
            "label": "I / you / we / they",
            "color": "emerald",
            "text": "Use <strong>have got</strong> with these subjects.",
            "example": "I have got a book. / They have got a car."
        },
        {
            "label": "He / she / it",
            "color": "blue",
            "text": "Use <strong>has got</strong> with <strong>he / she / it</strong>.",
            "example": "He has got a dog. / She has got a cat."
        },
        {
            "label": "Full forms",
            "color": "amber",
            "text": "At A1 it is easy to stay with full forms in negatives and questions: <strong>have not got / has not got</strong>, <strong>Have ... got?</strong>, <strong>Has ... got?</strong>.",
            "example": "We have not got a house. / Has she got a cat?"
        }
    ]
}

{
    "title": "1. Basic forms",
    "intro": "Remember which form goes with each subject.",
    "items": [
        {
            "label": "I / You / We / They",
            "title": "have got",
            "subtitle": "I have got a book. / They have got a car."
        },
        {
            "label": "He / She / It",
            "title": "has got",
            "subtitle": "He has got a dog. / She has got two books."
        },
        {
            "label": "Negative",
            "title": "have not got / has not got",
            "subtitle": "You have not got a cat. / He has not got a brother."
        },
        {
            "label": "Questions",
            "title": "Have / Has + subject + got",
            "subtitle": "Have you got a book? / Has she got a cat?"
        }
    ]
}

{
    "title": "2. When we use have got / has got",
    "sections": [
        {
            "label": "Objects and things",
            "color": "emerald",
            "description": "Use <strong>have got / has got</strong> when you talk about things a person has.",
            "examples": [
                {
                    "en": "I have got a book.",
                    "ua": "I have got a book."
                },
                {
                    "en": "They have got a car.",
                    "ua": "They have got a car."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "label": "Family and pets",
            "color": "blue",
            "description": "The pattern often describes relatives, pets, or people close to us.",
            "examples": [
                {
                    "en": "I have got a sister.",
                    "ua": "I have got a sister."
                },
                {
                    "en": "She has got a cat.",
                    "ua": "She has got a cat."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "label": "Negatives and questions",
            "color": "amber",
            "description": "At A1, full forms are the clearest choice: <strong>have not got / has not got</strong> and questions with <strong>Have / Has</strong> at the start.",
            "examples": [
                {
                    "en": "He has not got a brother.",
                    "ua": "He has not got a brother."
                },
                {
                    "en": "What have you got?",
                    "ua": "What have you got?"
                }
            ],
            "note": "📌 After <strong>have / has</strong> in this pattern, we use <strong>got</strong>."
        }
    ]
}

{
    "title": "3. Quick table",
    "intro": "One simple model for each sentence type.",
    "rows": [
        {
            "en": "I / You / We / They",
            "ua": "have got",
            "note": "We have got a house."
        },
        {
            "en": "He / She / It",
            "ua": "has got",
            "note": "She has got two books."
        },
        {
            "en": "Negative",
            "ua": "have not got / has not got",
            "note": "I have not got a car. / He has not got a brother."
        },
        {
            "en": "Question",
            "ua": "Have / Has + subject + got?",
            "note": "Have they got a car? / Has he got a dog?"
        }
    ],
    "warning": "📌 At this level, stay with the full forms: <strong>have got, has got, have not got, has not got</strong>."
}

{
    "title": "4. Short summary",
    "items": [
        "Use <strong>have got</strong> with <strong>I / you / we / they</strong>.",
        "Use <strong>has got</strong> with <strong>he / she / it</strong>.",
        "Negative: <strong>have not got / has not got</strong>.",
        "Question: <strong>Have / Has + subject + got?</strong>",
        "Wh-questions also keep <strong>have / has + subject + got</strong>: <strong>What have you got?</strong>, <strong>What has he got?</strong>"
    ]
}
